[4] Seizures in early infancy
Date: Mon 23 Apr 2018
Source: American Journal of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene [edited]
http://www.ajtmh.org/content/journals/10.4269/ajtmh.17-1020


Citation
Oliveira-Filho J, Felzemburgh R, Costa F, et al. Seizures as a complication of congenital Zika syndrome in early infancy. Am J Trop Med Hyg. 2018. doi: 10.4269/ajtmh.17-1020. [Epub ahead of print]

Zika virus transmission in Brazil was linked to a large outbreak of microcephaly but less is known about longer term anthropometric and neurological outcomes. We studied a cohort of infants born between [31 Oct 2015], and [9 Jan 2016], in a state maternity hospital, followed up for 101 plus/minus 28 days by home visits. Microcephaly (less than 2 standard deviations, Intergrowth standard) occurred in 62 of 412 (15 percent) births. Congenital Zika syndrome (CZS) was diagnosed in 29 patients. Among CZS patients, we observed a significant gain in anthropometric measures (P less 0.001) but no significant gain in percentile for these measures. The main neurological outcome was epilepsy, occurring in 48 percent of infants at a rate of 15.6 cases per 100 patient-months, frequently requiring multiple anti-seizure medications. The cumulative fatality rate was 7.4 percent (95 percent confidence interval: 2.1-23.4 percent). Health-care professionals should be alerted on the high risk of epilepsy and death associated with CZS in early infancy and the need to actively screen for seizures and initiate timely treatment.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Interestingly, a recently published study stated that babies exposed to Zika virus in utero but who are born with normal neuroimaging appear to develop in much the same way as do unexposed infants. At 6 months of age, the infants had neuromotor skills similar to those of unexposed controls. However, the authors stated that investigators need to determine how their work compares with studies from other parts of the world, where there have been observations that are more concerning in babies who have appeared normal at birth. (https://www.medpagetoday.com/meetingcoverage/pas/72749). - Mod.TY]

